JavaScript Day 1 – Introduction ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
What is JavaScript?

JavaScript is a programming language that makes web pages interactive.

HTML → Structure (Skeleton)

CSS → Style (Beauty)

JavaScript → Behavior (Brain)

For example:

Click a button
Validate a form
Show a popup
Fetch data from a server
Build dynamic websites
Example
HTML only
<button>Click Me</button>

Nothing happens when you click it.

HTML + JavaScript
<button onclick="sayHello()">Click Me</button>

<script>
function sayHello() {
    alert("Hello!");
}
</script>

Now clicking the button shows an alert.

Where can we write JavaScript?
1. Inline (Not recommended)
<button onclick="alert('Hello')">Click</button>
2. Internal JavaScript
<script>
    console.log("Hello");
</script>
3. External JavaScript ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐ (Recommended)

index.html

<script src="script.js"></script>

script.js

console.log("Hello JavaScript");

This is how real projects are organized.

Variables

A variable stores data.

Think of it as a box that holds a value.

Example:

Age Box → 25

Name Box → Priya
Declaring Variables

JavaScript provides three ways:

var
let
const
1. var (Older way)
var name = "Priya";

console.log(name);

Output

Priya
2. let ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
let age = 27;

console.log(age);

Output

27

The value can be changed later.

let age = 27;

age = 28;

console.log(age);

Output

28
3. const ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Used when the value should not change.

const country = "India";

console.log(country);

Output

India

Trying to change it causes an error.

const country = "India";

country = "USA";

❌ Error

Assignment to constant variable.
Difference Between var, let, and const
Feature	var	let	const
Can reassign?	✅ Yes	✅ Yes	❌ No
Can redeclare in same scope?	✅ Yes	❌ No	❌ No
Modern?	❌ No	✅ Yes	✅ Yes
Interview Tip

Use:

const by default
let if the value needs to change
Avoid var in modern JavaScript
Data Types

JavaScript has two categories:

Primitive Data Types
1. String
let name = "Priya";

Text inside quotes.

2. Number
let age = 27;

Integers and decimals are both number.

let price = 99.99;
3. Boolean

Only two values:

true

false

Example

let isLoggedIn = true;
4. Undefined

Declared but not assigned.

let city;

console.log(city);

Output

undefined
5. Null

Represents an intentional empty value.

let phone = null;
6. BigInt

For very large integers.

let big = 12345678901234567890n;
7. Symbol

Used to create unique identifiers.

let id = Symbol("id");

Not commonly used by beginners.

Non-Primitive Data Type
Object
let person = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27
};

Objects store data as key-value pairs.

Check Data Type

Use typeof.

let age = 27;

console.log(typeof age);

Output

number

More examples:

console.log(typeof "Hello");
string
console.log(typeof true);
boolean
console.log(typeof undefined);
undefined
console.log(typeof null);

Output:

object

⚠️ This is a well-known quirk in JavaScript. Although typeof null returns "object", null is actually a primitive value.

Comments

Comments are ignored by JavaScript and are used to explain code.

Single-line comment
// This is a comment

let age = 27;
Multi-line comment
/*
This is
a multi-line
comment
*/
Console Methods ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

The browser console is very useful for debugging.

console.log()
console.log("Hello");

Output

Hello
console.error()
console.error("Something went wrong");

Displays an error message.

console.warn()
console.warn("Warning!");

Displays a warning message.

console.table()
const student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27,
    city: "Coimbatore"
};

console.table(student);

Shows the object in a table format.

console.clear()
console.clear();

Clears the browser console.

Complete Example
// Variables
const name = "Priya";
let age = 27;
let city = "Coimbatore";

// Print values
console.log(name);
console.log(age);
console.log(city);

// Data types
console.log(typeof name);
console.log(typeof age);
console.log(typeof city);

// Warning
console.warn("Learning JavaScript");

// Error
console.error("Sample Error");

// Object
const student = {
    name: "Priya",
    age: 27,
    city: "Coimbatore"
};

console.table(student);
